<div id="review_3499628703" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3499628703" />
    <a title="Claire" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/89283877-claire"><img alt="Claire" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1595000452p2/89283877.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3499628703?book_show_action=true">Sep 26, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Claire" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Claire" href="/user/show/89283877-claire">Claire</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/89283877-claire?shelf=2020-read">2020-read</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/89283877-claire?shelf=make-a-movie">make-a-movie</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/89283877-claire?shelf=new-author">new-author</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/89283877-claire?shelf=different-timelines">different-timelines</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/89283877-claire?shelf=favourite-books">favourite-books</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/89283877-claire?shelf=loss">loss</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/89283877-claire?shelf=5-stars">5-stars</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/89283877-claire?shelf=i-cried">i-cried</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/89283877-claire?shelf=novels">novels</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3499628703" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer11075010708413034613">&quot;But ask yourself this: Have you ever lost someone you loved and wanted one more conversation, one more chance to make up for the time when you thought they would be here forever? If so, then you know you can go your whole life collecting days, and none will outweigh the one you wish you had back.<br/>What if you got it back?&quot;<br/><br/><br/>This. Book.<br/><br/>Can that just be the whole review? Because I&apos;m literally in shock right now.<br/><br/>Tip~ This is a read-in-one-sitting kind of book, so I&apos;d recommend to start it in the middl</span>
  <span id="freeText11075010708413034613" style="display:none">"But ask yourself this: Have you ever lost someone you loved and wanted one more conversation, one more chance to make up for the time when you thought they would be here forever? If so, then you know you can go your whole life collecting days, and none will outweigh the one you wish you had back.<br />What if you got it back?"<br /><br /><br />This. Book.<br /><br />Can that just be the whole review? Because I'm literally in shock right now.<br /><br />Tip~ This is a read-in-one-sitting kind of book, so I'd recommend to start it in the middle of the day, and you'll be finished by early evening. <br /><br />This was just amazing. Mitch Albom's books were recommended to me by a friend here on Goodreads, but I really wasn't prepared in any way for how emotional and just...eye-opening this book would be. I have a rule that I don't call an author one of my 'favourite authors' if I haven't read more than one of their books, but wow I can already see Albom at the top of my list.<br /><br />Charley Benetto has ruined his life. He's lost his job, destroyed his relationship with his family, and turned to alcohol to drown his sorrows. There's no going back for him. No redemption. So he decides to take his own life.<br /><br />But isn't there a second chance for everyone? When Charley decides that his life should end where it began, he makes his final journey in life to his hometown. But when he staggers in the door to his mother's old house, his late mother is sitting at the kitchen table, ready to give her son a reality check. <br /><br />Is she real? Was he dead? Were they in Heaven? Charley learns to accept that these questions really don't matter, because wouldn't we all give anything in the world to be with a lost loved one for just one more day? <br /><br />This book is the definition of 'short but powerful'. The story is told through multiple timelines: from the present, the time surrounding his mother's death, Charley's childhood, and then random memories. <br /><br />These snippets piece together a heartbreaking story, but one we all know. After someone dies, you realise all the times you didn't stick up for them, you'd give anything to apologise for this or that, to explain why you couldn't be there, to give them one last hug. This is a very emotional read, especially for someone with a particular loved one in mind.<br /><br />Could I rate this book anything but 5🌟? Of course not, don't be absurd. Going into this book, I was so extremely unprepared for the story I was about to read. I need Albom's other books. When are they making the movie?<br /><br />Rating: 🌟🌟🌟🌟🌟<br />Recommended for fans of: 'They Both Die at the End', 'The Little Prince' and 'Bridge to Terebithia'</span>
  <a data-text-id="11075010708413034613" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


